      <hedline>
        <hl1>Quirky Record Jackets</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Donald Howard letter comments on July 31 article on Teresa Sterne, pioneering former director of Nonesuch Records who was piano prodigy in her youth</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Scene-Stealer Behind the Scenes'' (Arts pages, July 31), about Teresa Sterne, the pioneering former director of Nonesuch Records who was a piano prodigy in her youth:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Scene-Stealer Behind the Scenes'' (Arts pages, July 31), about Teresa Sterne, the pioneering former director of Nonesuch Records who was a piano prodigy in her youth:</p>
        <p>Back in the heyday of LP records, I used to buy Nonesuch albums of Baroque music by artists I never heard of simply for the record jackets, which were unique in the industry.</p>
        <p>Nonesuch classical music records were instantly recognizable by the design on the front of the jacket, which always featured a wonderfully quirky full-color illustration. The subject matter varied widely, from instruments and musicians to 18th-century drawing rooms to depictions of classical mythology.</p>
        <p>The jackets were in marked contrast to those of other, better-known labels, which invariably displayed type against plain backgrounds or carried static portrait photographs of the performers.</p>
        <p>DONALD HOWARD  Poway, Calif., July 31, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
